ee   Skehan  ).","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Draighneáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Draighneán</i>’ (see   Drennan  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Thornber","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the five minor places in Yorkshire called Thornber, particularly Thornber in Halton West. The placenames derive from Old English <i>thorn</i> ‘thorn’ + <i>beorg</i> ‘hill, mound’.","Irish: adopted for various Irish names containing an element meaning ‘thorn’; compare   Thornton  ."]},{"name":"Thorton","meanings":["(1997: 465;2007: 2025; 2010: NA)","English: probably a shortened form of   Thornton  , or a habitational name from Thorton in Marnhull, Dorset, which has the same origin."]},{"name":"Skehan","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Sceacháin</b> or <b>Ó Sceacháin</b> ‘son (or descendant) of <i>Sceachán</i>’, a personal name probably based on a diminutive of <i>sceach</i> ‘briar, thorn bush’. The Gaelic name has sometimes been ‘translated’ as   Thornton  ."]}]},{"name":"Nicholas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Nicholas De Thorndon was born in 1318, in Besford, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 daughter with Nicholas de Thorndon."},"et":{"       1318–":"1318–Surnud","1288–1323":"1288–1323","1323–1404":"1323–1404","1318–Female":"1318–Surnud","1404":"1404","1323":"1323","1288":"1288","about 1323":"umbes 1323","       1318":"1318","1318":"1318","Besford, Worchestershire, England":"Besford, Worcestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Besford, Worcestershire, England":"Besford, Worcestershire, England"},"fi":{"       1318–":"1318–Kuollut","1288–1323":"1288–1323","1323–1404":"1323–1404","1318–Female":"1318–Kuollut","1404":"1404","1323":"1323","1288":"1288","about 1323":"noin 1323","       1318":"1318","1318":"1318","Besford, Worchestershire, England":"Besford, Worcestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Besford, Worcestershire, England":"Besford, Worcestershire, England"},"fr":{"       1318–":"1318–Décédée","1288–1323":"1288–1323","1323–1404":"1323–1404","1318–Female":"1318–Décédée","1404":"1404","1323":"1323","1288":"1288","about 1323":"environ 1323","       1318":"1318","1318":"1318","Besford, Worchestershire, England":"Besford, Worcestershire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Besford, Worcestershire, England":"Besford, Worcestershire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Mrs Nicholas De Thorndon est née en 1318, à Besford, Worcestershire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Elle a eu au moins 1 fille avec Nicholas de Thorndon."},"de":{"       1318–":"1318–Verstorben","1288–1323":"1288–1323","1323–1404":"1323–1404","1318–Female":"1318–Verstorben","1404":"1404","1323":"1323","1288":"1288","about 1323":"um 1323","       1318":"1318","1318":"1318","Besford, Worchestershire, England":"Besford, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","Besford, Worcestershire, England"